        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Denekamp</placeName> the <date>5 December <hi
                        rend="underline">1862</hi></date></p>
            <p rend="align(center)">My very dear uncle!</p>
            <p>That you may receive these<lb/> rules in the best health is my<lb/> upright
                    <sic>heartly</sic> wish.</p>
            <p>What is to me I find my as<lb/> well as possible thank God<lb/> and I hope to hear
                soon the same<lb/> from you my dear; and I wish<lb/> at the same time that our
                heavenly<lb/> father may let us <sic>life</sic> in the<lb/> best health yet many
                years <del>good</del> together<lb/>
                <add>אמן</add>. My dear uncle? I have <del>M<add>?</add></del> waited<lb/> already
                long at one letter from you<lb/> but in vain; although I well<lb/> receive your book
                every month<lb/> which is also good but I beg you<lb/> friendly that you may satisfy
                on me request;<lb/> and write me now a great letter<lb/> and you shall be assured
                that I<lb/> shall not be wanting to answer you<lb/> as soon as I have received your
                letter.</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>My father goes the day after<lb/> tomorrow at <placeName><hi rend="underline"
                        >Hamburg</hi></placeName> he has<lb/>
                <del>th</del> do there any business and take<lb/> this letter and the cheeses
                which<lb/> you receive annexed this t<del>h</del>ill there;<lb/> and I wish you of
                all my heart<del>h</del><lb/> that you <sic>my</sic> eat them in the best<lb/>
                health. I look yet often on your<lb/> picture and as often as I regard it<lb/> I
                think I would you were by us:<lb/> and wished well that it could be so,<lb/> it
                should do me the greatest pleasure<lb/> what I could enjoy.</p>
            <p>The war which is by you caused<lb/> everywhere, where are <sic>fabricks</sic><lb/> a
                great distress and bring about<lb/> much poverty; give God that it<lb/> may be
                almost on the end; then<lb/> unity makes power.</p>
            <p>Now my dear uncle! I know at<lb/> this time none news to write you,<lb/> another time
                more.</p>
            <p>Be saluted many times from me<lb/> and in the hope to receive soon<lb/> a great
                letter from you; I am and</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>I remain which the most respect<lb/> Your <sic>affectionated</sic> niece till in
                eternity</p>
            <p>
                <hi rend="underline">
                    <persName role="author">Jeanette Elkus</persName>
                </hi>
            </p>
            <p>
                <add>Hebrew</add>
            </p>
